    <name>
      <text>5.2.9 (Cos multiplied equation not exact positive)</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>What are the solutions to the equation {@eqn@} are there in the range \(0 < x < 180^\circ\)? Give your answer as a list to the nearest degree. For example if you believe the answers to be \(x = 10^\circ\) and \(x = 20^\circ\) then enter <code>[x=10,x=20]</code></p>
<p>[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Since we have {@eqn@} we see that \(\cos({@cc@}x\) must be positive, therefore we are looking for solutions in the first and fourth quadrants. Hence we can expect solutions of the form \({@cc@}x)\) or \(360^\circ - {@cc@}x\).
Thus we have, 
\[
{@cc@}x = {@rccx@} \qquad \mbox{and} \qquad {@360-rccx@}.
\]
However these aren't the only solutions since we require \(0 < x < 180^\circ\) we require \(0 < {@cc@}x < {@cc@}\cdot 180^\circ\). Thus to find the other solutions we use the fact that adding multiples of \(360^\circ\) doesn't alter the value of \(\cos {@cc@}x\) and we keep doing this until we pass \({@cc*180@}^\circ\). Thus in this case we have 
\[
{@cc@}x = {@rccx@} \mbox{ and } {@360-rccx@} \mbox{ and } {@360+rccx@}  
\]
Hence we can divide all of these by {@cc@} to obtain
\[
x = {@soln1@} \mbox{ or } {@soln2@} \mbox{ or } {@soln3@},
\]
and these are the only solutions in the given range.
</p>]]></text>
